<doc id="524910" wikidata="Q2994718" url="?curid=524910" title="Voiced palatal implosive">
<text>The voiced palatal implosive is a type of consonantal sound, used in some spoken languages. The symbol in the International Phonetic Alphabet that represents this sound is , and the equivalent X-SAMPA symbol is codice_1. Typographically, the IPA symbol is a dotless lowercase letter &quot;j&quot; with a horizontal stroke that was initially created by turning the type for a lowercase letter &quot;f&quot; (the symbol for the voiced palatal stop) and a rightward hook (the diacritic for implosives). A very similar-looking letter, (an with a tail), is used in Ewe for .

